ity in a corpus of official documents (I–II CE) -- t12 Orthographic variation and register in the corpus of Greek documentary papyri (300 BCE–800 CE) -- t13 The Greek phonology of a tax collector in Egypt in the first century CE -- t14 Metrical variation in Byzantine colophons (XI–XV CE): The example of ἡ μὲν χεὶρ ἡ γράψασα -- t15 Arguing and narrating: Text type and linguistic variation in tenth-century Greek -- t16 The distinctiveness of syntax for varieties of Post-classical and Byzantine Greek: Linguistic upgrading from the third century BCE to the tenth century CE -- tIndex locorum -- tIndex nominum -- tIndex rerum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLinguistic varieties such as female speech, foreigner talk, and colloquial language have not gone unnoticed when it comes to Classical Greek, but little is known about later periods of the Greek language. In this collective volume leading experts in the field outline some of the most important varieties of Post-classical and Byzantine Greek, basing themselves on a broad range of literary and documentary sources, and advancing a number of innovative methodologies. Close attention is paid to the linguistic features that characterize these varieties, with in-depth discussions of lexical, morpho-syntactic, orthographic, and metrical variation, as well as the interrelationship between these different types of variation. The volume thus offers valuable insights into the nature of Post-classical and Byzantine Greek, laying the foundation for future studies of linguistic variation in these later stages of the language, while at the same time providing a point of comparison for Classical Greek scholarship  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aClassical languagesxVariation. 0aG